[1] Philippines (Western Visayas)
Date: Fri 7 Dec 2018
Source: Philippine News Agency (PNA) [excerpted, edited]
http://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1056069


The incidence of measles in Western Visayas has reached alarming levels with 170 cases and 3 suspected deaths recorded as of 6 Dec 2018 by the Department of Health-Center for Health Development (DOH-CHD) 6.

Dr. Mary Jane Roches Juanico, medical coordinator for the child health program, said that last month [November 2018], they recorded 130 cases, with 29 from the Bureau of Jail Management and Penology (BJMP) in Bacolod.

"The cases are under investigation. We are waiting for the results if indeed they are measles cases," she said in an interview on the sidelines of the DOH regional recognition of partners and stakeholders held at the Eon Centennial Resort in Alta Tierra in Jaro district in this city on Fri 7 Dec 2018.

Juanico said they have used various strategies to address the concern, including the door-to-door campaign.

The DOH-CHD 6 in October 2018 launched the supplemental immunization activity for measles, rubella, and oral polio vaccine (MR-OPV). The 1st phase was rolled out in 25 areas in Western Visayas, covering 339 183 children.

However, at the end of the one-month activity, they only covered 43 percent of their target population.

Records showed that 145 255 children, aged 6-59 months, were vaccinated for measles and rubella, and 147 055 were administered the OPV.

"We are still doing catch up for those children that we have missed until 14 Dec 2018," she said.

She said that during their program implementation review on 6 Dec 2018, they shared that they "really had a challenge in terms of social mobilization and advocacy, campaigning for the high turnout. It is mainly because of the refusal of our parents or caregivers due to the Dengvaxia scare. Our confidence rating in terms of the immunization program is not that good," she said.

The 2nd phase that will be administered during the 1st and 2nd quarter of 2019 will cover 42 areas or those that are considered as bordering areas or with the highest number of missed children. The 2nd phase will cover 258 443 children.

[Byline: Perla Lena]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The problems encountered following administration of the dengue vaccine have had far reaching consequences beyond dengue. People have extrapolated to other well-tested vaccines such as measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine. The doctors and schools need to educate parents that MMR is much safer than getting the disease and very effective. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] London ex Israel
Date: Wed 5 Dec 2018
Source: Israel National News [excerpted, edited]
http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/255733


A measles epidemic plaguing Israel's haredi community has spread to the Jewish community in northern London, British news outlets have reported.

Haredi communities in New York City and Jerusalem have seen a surge in the number of measles infections since the spring, attributed in part to the relatively large number of people in those communities who have not been vaccinated.

By the end of October 2018, nearly 900 cases of measles had been reported in Israel, with roughly 60% of those infected coming from the haredi sector.

The epidemic has since spread to the Orthodox Jewish community in northern London, with dozens of cases reported over the past 2 months.

Close to 70 members of London's Orthodox Jewish community have been infected since October 2018, The Times reported. The majority of those infected had not been vaccinated, the report noted.

According to a report by the London-based Jewish Chronicle, the epidemic was spread when local haredi Jews visited Jerusalem for the Rosh Hashanah, Yom Kippur, and Sukkot festival season, then returned to Britain in early October 2018, carrying the disease.

One physician in Stamford Hill, a north London neighborhood with a large haredi Jewish population, attributed the outbreak in part to the lower vaccination rates in the Orthodox community.

"Over the last 4-6 weeks, we've known there was a measles outbreak among the Charedi community in Israel. It has now reached our shores," Dr. Joseph Spitzer said in an interview with the Chronicle.

Vaccination rates are, Dr. Spitzer continued, "definitely lower than the general population, and there are lots of reasons for that. Some people will say it is due to the fact that they have large families and, therefore, they cannot keep up with the immunizations. There is also a little bit of what you might call 'haredi urban myth' and a mistrust of the secular authorities."

[Byline: David Rosenberg]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Haredi is the Hebrew term for the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community. The outbreak in Israel and an ensuing outbreak in the U.S. have hit ultra-Orthodox Jewish enclaves in both countries particularly hard. Dozens have contracted the virus in New York and New Jersey, and more than 1400 people -- the majority of them haredi -- have fallen ill in Israel, half of them in October 2018 alone. See the New York and New Jersey posts that follow below. - Mod.LK]

******
[3] New York (Rockland)
Date: Fri 7 Dec 2018
Source: Patch [excerpted, edited]
https://patch.com/new-york/newcity/measles-outbreak-rockland-cases-hit-90


Another case of measles was confirmed in Rockland County on Fri 7 Dec 2018. To date, there are 90 confirmed cases with 7 more suspected. The health department is continuing to investigate the suspected cases.

The entire county should be considered at risk. Even people previously considered immune -- anyone born before 1957 and anyone who has received 2 doses of measles vaccine -- could catch the highly contagious disease.

Health officials have kept tightened restrictions on schools in the geographic area where the outbreak is concentrated. All schools in New Square and any school in Spring Valley or Monsey where the immunization rate is lower than 80 percent, must keep un- or under-vaccinated students at home.

The restrictions, which affect 34 schools, will apply until 21 days after the last measles case is confirmed in the county, and officials acknowledge that that could be months away.

The county also wants children to be vaccinated earlier than usual. Instead of waiting till 12 months, any child 6 months or older or any adult who has not received their 1st MMR vaccine yet should get their 1st MMR vaccine now.

[Byline: Michael Woyton]

