[5] Latin America and the Caribbean (Chile imported)
Date: Tue 4 Dec 2018
Source: Outbreak News Today [excerpted, edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/chile-reports-1st-measles-cases-43132/


Chilean health officials have reported the 1st 2 measles cases of 2018. Both are confirmed, imported cases reported in November 2018.

According to the Chile Public Health Institute (ISP): The 1st case is a 42-year-old woman of Colombian nationality who had rash onset on 8 Nov 2018 and has been a resident of Chile for more than 10 years. The probable place of infection might be Ecuador or Colombia, as the case had stayed in both countries in the days prior to symptom onset. No secondary cases have been confirmed. Genotyping results indicated genotype D8, with the lineage results pending.

The 2nd case is a 4-year-old male child of Venezuelan nationality who had rash onset on 23 Nov 2018. The case arrived in Chile on 18 Nov 2018 by land from the city of Maracaibo, Zulia State, Venezuela; he traveled through Colombia, Ecuador, and Peru prior to reaching Chile through the northern part of the country. No secondary cases have been confirmed. Laboratory confirmation was carried out through serological tests and by reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR); genotyping results indicated genotype D8, with the lineage results pending.

The last outbreak associated with imported cases in Chile was in 2015, with 9 confirmed cases reported (viral genotype H1).

In the Americas as of 30 Nov 2018, a total of 16 766 confirmed measles cases, including 86 deaths, have been reported in 12 countries of the region.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Incidence of measles has increased tremendously in the Americas, largely due to low levels of vaccination and import from countries where measles is more prevalent. Genotyping helps identify origin and movement of the outbreaks. The WHO currently recognizes 8 clades, designated A, B, C, D, E, F, G, and H. Within these clades, there are 23 recognized genotypes, designated A, B1, B2, B3, C1, C2, D1, D2, D3, D4, D5, D6, D7, D8, D9, D10, E, F, G1, G2, G3, H1, and H2, and 1 provisional genotype, d11. Virologic surveillance for measles was initiated in response to the global measles resurgence that occurred in the late 1980s (Rota JS et al. Virology, 1992, vol. 188:135). These activities have increased significantly during the past 10 years because of the expansion of LabNet (excerpted from https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/204/suppl_1/S514/2194335). - Mod.LK]
